@endnode
 
@node dist "Distribution"

Any one can use it free.

@endnode


@node notes "Notes"

The library being written in AmigaE uses Address registers A4 & A5 on the 
processor chip.

It also uses Registers D6 & D7 as scratch registers.

Since I write almost entirely in E the c include (highprecision.h) might
have errors.Any correction would be appreciated.

I have included the source for "Century Calc"
a 100 digit workbench calculator.
The main reason I wrote was to test the library.

@endnode

@node future "Future"
I hope to make Version 2 faster with assembler.
I also hope to add Log and Trig function.

I will not release Version 2 unless I get 10 requests for it.
@endnode

@node cmds "Complete"
To install copy HighPrecision.library to LIBS:
Copy includes to where you keep them.

Unless stated otherwise all routines return a pointer to the result variable.
This so you can chain operations.
example      HpAdd(a,HpMul(q,r,s),b)
instead of   HpMul(q,r,s)
             HpAdd(a,s,b)



HpSetup(a)
This routine sets the length of your variable.
a is a signed LONG (32 bit) <=2147483648
If out put is zero then it failed, probably for lack of memory.
Always use this just after you open the library or your program
will crash.
Usage     test:=HpSetup(LEN)

See:HpResize

HpResize(a)
This routine resets the length of your variable.
It can only reset a variable shorter than the length used in HpSetup
If you use a larger number it does nothing.
Usage     HpResize(NEWLEN)

See:HpSetup


HpMakeVar()
This routine makes an HP varible.
Usage     varible:=HpMakeVar()
you previously define varible as an unsignedlong.

See:HpUnMakeVar,HpMakeStr


HpUnMakeVar(a)
This routine destroys an HP varible.
Usage     HpUnMakeVar(varible)
Do not try to use this varible after useing this routine or your program will
crash.

See:HpMakeVar


HpMakeStr()
This routine will set up a string arraythat is the maximum length as
specified by HpSetup(LEN)
Usage     pointer:=HpMakeStr()
pointer is a pointer to an array of CHAR.

See:HpMakeVar

Fp2hp(a,b)
This routine converts an IEEE float to an HP variable.
Usage     Fp2hp(a,b)
a is a floating point number,b is an HP number
The routine outputs b so you can chain functions together.

See:Hp2fp


Hp2fp(a)
This routine converts an HP to a IEEE floating point number.
Usage     B:=Hp2fp(a)
b is a floating point number,a is an HP number

See: Fp2hp

Int2hp(a,b)
This routine converts an Integer to HP.
Usage     Int2hp(a,b)
a is a signed 32 bit integer,b is AN HP
The routine also returns a pointer to b.

See: Hp2int


Hp2int(a)
This routine converts an HP to a signed 32 bit integer
Str2hp(a,b)                 ptr to STR,LONG ptr to hp
Usage     b:=Hp2int(a)
b is the integer,a is the HP
if the HP is larger than the limits then a= +-$7fff

See: Int2hp

Hp2str(a,b,c)(A0,D1,D0)
This routine convers an HP to a string as set up by HpMakeStr()
Usage    Hp2Str(a,b,c)
The routine returnes a pointer to the string.
a is th HP to be converted,b is the string,c is the switches.
The switches are 
1 sets up the exponent in scientific notation, otherwise 10000 would be 10e3
when set it is 1e4.
2 forces exponent even if not needed. 10000 would be 10e3 otherwise 10000.
4 shows extra zeros. 10000 would be 10000.00000

See: Str2hp


Str2hp(a,b)
This routine converts a string to an HP
Usage Str2hp(a,b)  OR Str2hp('234',b)
a is a pointer to a string,b is an HP
The routine returns the pointer to b.
Examples of strings; '3.14' '3,14' '3.14e7' '3.14E7'
'e' or 'E' precedes the exponent
'.' or ',' is the decimal point.

See: Hp2str



HpAdd(a,b,c)
This routine adds 2 HP numberrs. c:=a+b
Usage HpAdd(a,b,c)
a is an HP
b is an HP
c is the HP the result is sent to.it may be the same as a or b if you wish.
the routine returns c

See: HpSub,HpMul,HpDiv


HpSub(a,b,c)
This routine subtracts b from a.c:=a-b.
Usage  HpSub(a,b,c)
a is an HP
b is an HP
c is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a or b if you wish.

See: Hpadd,HpMul,HpDiv

HpMul(a,b,c)
This routine multiplies 2 HP numbers, c:=a*b
Usage HpMul(a,b,c)
a is an HP
b is an HP
c is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a or b if you wish.

See: Hpadd,HpSub,HpDiv


HpDiv(a,b,c)
This routine Devides one HP by another.c:=a/b
Usage  HpDiv(a,b,c)
a is an HP
b is an HP
c is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a or b if you wish.

See: Hpadd,HpSub,HpMul


HpPower(a,b,c)
This routine takes a to the power b.
Usage HpPower(a,b,c) or HpPower(a,3,c) 
a is an HP
b is a  signed integer -2147483647<=b<=2147483647.Don't use a float or
        an HP,the results would be very wrong.
c is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.



HpSqrt(a,b)
THis routine takes the square root,b:=Sqrt(a)
Usage HpSqrt(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.


HpRec(a,b)
This routine takes the reciprical.b:=1/a
Usage  HpRec(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.



HpCopy(a,b)
This routine copis one variable to another.b:=a
Usage HpCopy(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to.
b is returned for chaining.


HpClear(a)
This routine ssets the varible to zero. a:=0
Usage  HpClear(a)
a is an HP
a is returned for chaining.


HpCmp(a,b,c)
This routine compares two numbers to see if they are the same to the len
     set by the third variable.
Usage   d:=HpCmp(a,b,c) or d:=HpCmp(a,b,4)
a is an HP
b is an HP
c is a positive integer,if it is zero or larger then the maximum length 
       then it compares to the length set by HpSetUp(LEN)
the out put is zero if equal
if a>b then d:=1
if b>a then d:=-1



HpEq(a,b)
This routine comapres two number and tells to what length thay are equal
Usage c:=HpEq(a,b)
a is an HP
b is an HP



HpSign(a)
This routine tells you the sign of a number
Usage b:=HpSign(a)
a is an HP
b is 1 if a is positive
b is -1 if a is negative
b is zero if a is zero



HpAbs(a,b)
This routine take the aboulute value of a number.
Usage HpAbs(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.


HpChs(a,b)
This routine Changes the sign of a number.b:=-a
Usage  HpChs(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.


HpHalf(a,b)
This routine devides a number in half.b:=a/2
Usage HpHalf(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.


HpDouble(a,b)
This routine doubles a number.b:=a*2
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.


HpInt(a,b)
This routine drop everything to the right of the decimal point.
Usage HpInt(a,b)
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.


HpFrc(a,b)
This routine drops everything to the left of the decimal point.
a is an HP
b is the HP the result is sent to,it may be the same as a if you wish.
b is returned for chaining.














































@endnode
